# Publishing a Cloud-Lamp firmware release — mandatory full checklist

This rule is `alwaysApply: true` **specifically so it can never be missed** — whenever the
user asks to publish/release/ship/cut an OTA update (in any wording), run this *entire*
checklist, in order. Never jump straight to bumping the version or running
`tools/release.sh` in isolation — a "release" in this project always means the checklist
below, not just the binary. Canonical, full-detail doc for the mechanics:
`docs/firmware-updates.md#publishing-a-release-builder-workflow`; background on *why*
releases work this way: `docs/cloud-lamp-design.md#project-status`.

1. **Figure out the version bump.** Compare against the last released `project_version`
   (git history / the last `docs/firmware-dist/cloud-lamp/manifest.json`). Use this
   project's existing convention (see the `Phase: vX.Y.Z` changelog entries in
   `docs/cloud-lamp-design.md#project-status` for precedent):
   - **Patch (Z)** — bug fixes, effect/behaviour tuning, UI polish, docs-only changes, no
     new user-facing capability.
   - **Minor (Y)** — a new effect, setting, feature, or a real behavioural fix a user would
     notice (e.g. the v2.5.0 power-loss/OTA-state fixes).
   - **Major (X)** — not used yet on this project; reserve for breaking changes.
   If the right bump isn't obvious, **stop and ask the user**, stating your recommendation
   and reasoning rather than silently picking one.
2. **Bump `project_version`** in `cloud-lamp.yaml`'s `substitutions` block. Never
   re-publish an already-seen version string — the online updater won't offer it.
3. **Audit and fix `README.md`** end-to-end against the *current* firmware/web app/docs —
   not just the parts related to the latest change. Check the feature list, effect
   count/list, hardware table, getting-started steps, documentation table, and repository
   layout still match reality (grep the actual source: `cloud-lamp.yaml` substitutions,
   `effects.yaml` effect names, `web/app.html` language list, file existence for every
   path mentioned). Fix anything stale, wrong, or missing.
4. **Audit and fix `docs/user-manual.md`**, then rebuild the PDF:
   `python3 tools/build-manual.py`. Follow `.cursor/rules/manual-release-check.mdc` for the
   specific sections to re-verify (button gestures, Wi-Fi flow, update flow, sticker table,
   effect count, language list, permanent manual URL — **never change that URL**). The
   cover page's version/date come from `cloud-lamp.yaml` automatically — never hardcode a
   version in the markdown source.
5. **Think beyond README/PDF** — for *this specific* batch of changes, what else could now
   be stale? At minimum check: `docs/cloud-lamp-design.md` (add/close out a changelog entry
   for this version), `docs/firmware-updates.md`, `docs/device-credentials.md` (if sticker
   fields/naming changed), `tools/mock-device.py` (if effects/entities changed), and any
   other doc that names a version number, effect, or entity that changed. Don't limit
   yourself to this list — reason about what this specific change actually touched.
6. **Security scan — before committing anything, since this whole repo is public.**
   Everything from steps 1–5 (README, manual markdown + rebuilt PDF, design doc, any other
   touched file) is about to become a public GitHub commit. Before staging:
   - Grep the diff for every real value in `secrets.yaml` (Wi-Fi SSID/password, MQTT
     broker host/user/password, anything else it holds). None of those may appear
     literally anywhere in the repo — the *only* exception is the shared, deliberately
     public AP + OTA password already documented in `docs/device-credentials.md`.
   - Confirm `secrets.yaml` itself, any `.env` file, and the Ed25519 **private** signing
     key are not staged (they must never be tracked — the key lives outside the repo by
     design, see step 8).
   - Scan for anything else that shouldn't be public but could've been pasted in while
     debugging: real IP addresses/hostnames from your own network, personal contact info,
     device serials tied to a specific unit, API tokens, device-flow/login codes, etc.
   - This covers the *docs and repo*; it's in addition to (not a replacement for) the
     binary-level secret scan `tools/release.sh` already runs on the compiled firmware in
     step 9.
   - If you find anything, stop and remove it before committing — don't publish first and
     clean up after. Git history keeps old commits visible even once a file is edited
     later, so anything that already leaked needs the credential rotated, not just a
     follow-up commit; flag that to the user immediately rather than silently fixing it.
7. **Commit the source + doc changes** (version bump, README, manual, PDF, code, and any
   other files from steps 1–5, now scanned per step 6) as one clean commit *before* running
   `tools/release.sh` — keep the release commit that script makes limited to the binary +
   manifest.
8. **Run `tools/release.sh`** from the repo root. In order it: compiles the **public**
   build (`cloud-lamp.yaml` — never `cloud-lamp-dev.yaml`, which has compiled-in Wi-Fi
   credentials) and scans the binary for secrets; writes `docs/firmware-dist/cloud-lamp/`
   (the `.bin` + `manifest.json`); **signs** the manifest with the Ed25519 private key kept
   **outside this repo** (default `~/.cloud-lamp-release-secrets/ota-ed25519-private.key`,
   override via `$RELEASE_SIGNING_KEY` — see `docs/firmware-updates.md#key-custody`); then
   **publishes** by committing + pushing `docs/firmware-dist/cloud-lamp/` (and, via that
   same `git push`, the commit from step 7) to GitHub.
9. **That single `git push` is the entire publish step for the OTA channel.** `docs/` is
   this repo's GitHub Pages source, served at the custom domain
   `cloud-lamp.ddproductions.de` over **plain HTTP** (not HTTPS — "Enforce HTTPS" is
   deliberately off; see `docs/firmware-updates.md#plain-http--ed25519-signing`), which is
   exactly the URL every lamp polls (`update_manifest_url` in `cloud-lamp.yaml`). There is
   no separate upload target, FTP step, or CDN to keep in sync.
10. **`tools/release.sh` also tags the release and creates a GitHub Release** (`vX.Y.Z`,
    with the `.bin` attached) via the `gh` CLI — see
    `docs/firmware-updates.md#github-releases-human-facing-downloads`. This is purely a
    human-facing download/browse page; it's unrelated to how the lamp itself updates, and
    the script skips it gracefully (warning, not a failure) if `gh` isn't
    installed/authenticated on the release machine. Don't treat a skipped GitHub Release
    as a failed publish — the OTA channel (steps 8–9) is what devices depend on.
11. **Verify the live manifest**, e.g. `curl http://cloud-lamp.ddproductions.de/firmware-dist/cloud-lamp/manifest.json`
    and confirm it reports the new version. GitHub Pages can take a minute or two to
    redeploy after the push — if it still shows the old version, wait and re-check rather
    than assuming something failed.
12. Devices pick it up automatically (checked every 6 h and shortly after boot), or
    immediately if the owner presses "Check for updates now" in the web app.
13. **Post a short release report as your final reply — mandatory, every time.** Right
    after the checklist finishes (success, partial, or blocked), give the user a compact
    report, not a play-by-play of the steps above. Target ~6-10 lines total:
    - **Version:** old → new, and which bump size (patch/minor/major).
    - **Changes:** the actual user-facing/behavioural changes in this release, 1 line each
      (not "updated README" — the *content* change, e.g. "Ring Ripple effect added").
    - **Docs touched:** one line naming which files got real edits (or "none needed" if a
      full audit genuinely found nothing stale — don't skip the audit just because nothing
      changed last time).
    - **Published:** confirm the live manifest now shows the new version (from step 11),
      and whether the GitHub Release was created or skipped (and why, if skipped).
    - **Security:** one line confirming step 6's scan found nothing (or exactly what it
      found and how it was handled — see step 6's rotation note if something had already
      leaked).
    - **Not done / blocked:** anything from steps 1–11 that didn't complete, with the exact
      reason — never silently omit a skipped or failed step.
    Keep it scannable — short bullets, no restating this checklist's mechanics back to the
    user.

Re-running `tools/release.sh` after a failed/partial push is safe — it produces the exact
same version/MD5/signature every time.

**If asked to troubleshoot instead of publish** (e.g. "a lamp won't update" / "stuck on an
old version"), see `docs/firmware-updates.md#stuck-on-an-old-version-with-up-to-date-showing`
first — do not skip straight to re-publishing.
